        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-11-19T11:37:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-11-19T11:07:00-05:00" n="589"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d589">
                <head>589. Memorandum of a Conference With the President, White House, Washington,
                    November 19, 1956, 11:07–11:37 a.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d589fn1"
                        >Source: Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Diaries. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>. The time of the meeting is
                        from the record of the President’s Daily Appointments. (<hi rend="italic"
                            >Ibid.</hi>)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" from="1956-11-19T11:07:00-05:00"
                            to="1956-11-19T11:37:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 19, 1956</hi>, <hi rend="italic">11:07–11:37
                                a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>OTHERS PRESENT</head>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Colonel <persName corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of unrelated subjects.]</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName> said he was inclined to feel
                    that there has been some improvement in the general situation in the last day or
                    two, although nothing marked as yet. He referred to indications of difficulties
                    within the Soviet ruling group, and also to recent exchanges between ourselves
                    and the Arab countries, including instructions to <persName corresp="#p_WGE1"
                        >Wadsworth</persName> to give King <persName corresp="#p_SAA1"
                        >Saud</persName> our thinking regarding the developing oil situation.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d589fn2">Telegram 182, <ref target="#d586">Document
                        586</ref>.</note> The President reiterated strongly his feeling that we
                    should be trying to build up <persName corresp="#p_SAA1">Saud</persName> as an
                    element of strength and stability in the Middle East.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName> reported that pressure is being
                    generated by the British for large <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> forces to
                    go into Egypt. They evidently feel they need this action as a means of saving
                    face regarding their own withdrawal from Port Said. Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName> said, in his opinion, we must back up
                        <persName corresp="#p_HD1">Hammarskjold</persName> regarding <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> insistence that the British and French withdraw
                    very strongly. The President said that when the <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> forces go into the area, so long as they are of reasonable
                    size—enough to prevent brigandage—the whole <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                    prestige is pledged, and the question of exact numbers is not too important.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName> referred finally to reports
                    that are being received of tensions within the British Government and Cabinet at
                    the present time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">G</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Colonel CE, U S Army</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
